sus Medicine: The Debate over Drug Use in the 1960s -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCreating Postwar Canada showcases new research on this complex period, exploring postwar Canada's diverse symbols and battlegrounds. Contributors to the first half of the collection consider evolving definitions of the nation, examining the ways in which Canada was reimagined to include both the Canadian North and landscapes structured by trade and commerce. The essays in the latter half analyze debates on shopping hours, professional striptease, the "provider" role of fathers, interracial adoption, sexuality on campus, and illegal drug use, issues that shaped how the country defined itself in sociocultural and political terms. This collection contributes to the historiography of nationalism, gender and the family, consumer cultures, and countercultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocial changezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aAnastakis, Dimitry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelliveau, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBédard, Éric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDawson, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubinsky, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFahrni, Magda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHigh, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartel, Marcel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPenfold, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRos